It's an insightful morning on Parkaalaman with the theme"𝗔𝗰𝗰𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗔𝘂𝗱𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗣𝗮𝗿𝗸𝘀 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗕𝘂𝗶𝗹𝘁 𝗘𝗻𝘃𝗶𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁" with guest speakers Ar. Justin Owen S. Francisco and Engr. Miche'l Rainel M. Regalario. This event promotes the importance of making parks accessible. This has been made possible through National Parks Development Committee (NPDC), in partnership with United Architects of the Philippines (UAP) - Quezon City Central Chapter and Architects for Accessibility (AFA). A lively and interesting historical tour led by the Travelling Salakot followed in the afternoon. Thank you for the invite NPDC! I am hopeful to see you achieve this inclusivity milestone for Rizal Park! 💚 Mabuhay! #parks #npdc #PhilippineParks #bp344 #RizalPark #accessibleparks #inclusivity #inclusivedesign #parkmanagement

Oftentimes we think that if we do the right things, people will like us. The funny thing is when you do the right things, there will be people who'll dislike you. But know that there are people who'll like working with you. There will be people who'll rally behind you. Some people see and understand what you are bringing to the table. When working, ask yourself "What value am I adding here? How can I help fast-track the process? How can I help manage the timelines? How can I contribute to managing the company's resources better?". You're not here to please everyone. You're here to do what must be done. 𝗧𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀 𝗮𝗿𝗲 𝗴𝗼𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗾𝘂𝗶𝗲𝘁. Quiet quitting, quiet vacationing, quiet managing, quiet hiring, quiet firing. Adding another to the list will surely not hurt. Let's add 𝘘𝘶𝘪𝘦𝘵 𝘎𝘳𝘰𝘸𝘪𝘯𝘨 📈 Growing quietly may mean taking on that pottery class you've been putting off for the longest time, it may mean starting to save a part of your salary every payday, using that free gym pass, or taking that postgraduate course, listening to that podcast, reading that book, connecting to a spiritual family, recreating that recipe, etc. Plants grow quietly too. The seeds break. The roots pierce the soil. The leaves multiply. The stem elongates. The branches fan out. Some bloom, some become hardy, some become majestic! To promote the importance of making parks accessible, the National Parks Development Committee (NPDC), in partnership with United Architects of the Philippines (UAP) - Quezon City Central Chapter and Architects for Accessibility (AFA), will hold a seminar entitled "𝗔𝗰𝗰𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗔𝘂𝗱𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗣𝗮𝗿𝗸𝘀 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗕𝘂𝗶𝗹𝘁 𝗘𝗻𝘃𝗶𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁" on 20 July 2024 (Saturday), 8:00 AM at The Gallery, Rizal Park Luneta with guest speaker Ar. Justin Owen S. Francisco with Engr. Miche'l Rainel M. Regalario. Register now using the QR code below! Limited slots available. #parks #accesibilitylaw #PhilippineParks #freeevent #freeseminar #landscapearchitecture

𝗠𝗲𝗶𝗷𝗶 𝗝𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘂 𝗙𝗼𝗿𝗲𝘀𝘁 | 𝘚𝘩𝘪𝘣𝘶𝘺𝘢, 𝘛𝘰𝘬𝘺𝘰, 𝘑𝘢𝘱𝘢𝘯 This is a sacred forest covering 70 hectares of land, with 234 varieties of trees donated from all over Japan and planted by 110,000 volunteers. The criteria for choosing the trees were based on how they'd look in 100 to 200 years. Walking under these ginormous trees, one would immediately feel the significantly cooler temperature.
